	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Getting high-quality scans of some of the standardised crap (i.e. Nintendo's seal of approval) really isn't that hard.  Scan, apply a couple default Photoshop filters, clean up some of the borders/edges, adjust brightness/contrast to make up for scanner quality, and voila.</div>
<br />That might get you in trouble with the law. The "Official Nintendo Seal" is a trademark. It'd be better for someone to design a custom nesdev seal that can be used on any program developed in the homebrew community that has been successfully tested on NES hardware.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


